<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="26" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,1183,2036]" pageId="4" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1364,1388]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="26" reason="1">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet is a compound noun (Latin) in apposition composed of “crispus” (=stiff, in terms of hair) and “venter” (of the abdomen), referring to the stiff setae present on the ventral side of male abdomen.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="26" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,1183,2036]" pageId="4" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,1471,1496]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="26" reason="1">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This species is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Ruiz, 2011" authorityName="Ruiz" authorityYear="2011" box="[609,732,1472,1496]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Soesilarishius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="4" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="minimus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[609,732,1472,1496]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="26">S. minimus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[739,828,1472,1496]" pageId="4" pageNumber="26">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[739,828,1472,1496]" pageId="4" pageNumber="26" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
for the small size and boxy carapace (see 
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 6–9" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1839,1862]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,331,1815]" captionTargetId="figure-149@3.[151,1436,331,1815]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 6–9. Soesilarishius minimus sp. nov. 6 male habitus (paratype IBSP 160758); 7 female habitus (paratype IBSP 160711). Soesilarishius crispiventer sp. nov. 8 male habitus (paratype IBSP 160801); 9 female habitus (paratype IBSP 160841)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5280704" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5280704/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="26">Figs 6–7, 8– 9</figureCitation>
), but can easily be distinguished from that and the remaining known species by having a long, spiraled embolus in the male palp (
<figureCitation box="[349,478,1543,1567]" captionStart="FIGURES 10–14" captionStartId="5.[151,258,1573,1594]" captionTargetBox="[171,1419,205,1524]" captionTargetId="figure-215@5.[151,1436,195,1549]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 10–14. Soesilarishius crispiventer sp. nov. 10–12 left male palp (10 ventral, 11 retroventral, 12 retrolateral); 13 epigyne, ventral view; 14 vulva, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5280706" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5280706/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="26">Figs 10–12</figureCitation>
) and long, sinuous copulation ducts (
<figureCitation box="[901,1029,1543,1567]" captionStart="FIGURES 10–14" captionStartId="5.[151,258,1573,1594]" captionTargetBox="[171,1419,205,1524]" captionTargetId="figure-215@5.[151,1436,195,1549]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 10–14. Soesilarishius crispiventer sp. nov. 10–12 left male palp (10 ventral, 11 retroventral, 12 retrolateral); 13 epigyne, ventral view; 14 vulva, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5280706" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5280706/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="26">Figs 13–14</figureCitation>
) and anteriorly dislocated pocket in the epigyne (
<figureCitation box="[296,379,1580,1604]" captionStart="FIGURES 10–14" captionStartId="5.[151,258,1573,1594]" captionTargetBox="[171,1419,205,1524]" captionTargetId="figure-215@5.[151,1436,195,1549]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 10–14. Soesilarishius crispiventer sp. nov. 10–12 left male palp (10 ventral, 11 retroventral, 12 retrolateral); 13 epigyne, ventral view; 14 vulva, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5280706" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5280706/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="26">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="26" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,1183,2036]" pageId="4" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1616,1640]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="26" reason="1">Remarks.</emphasis>
Despite males of this species having a spiraled embolus at the distal end of the tegulum, this embolus curls to the opposite direction when compared to the typical euophryine spiraled embolus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="28" pageId="4" pageNumber="26" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,1183,2036]" pageId="4" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,542,1687,1712]" pageId="4" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis box="[199,344,1687,1712]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="26" reason="1">Description.</emphasis>
Male 
<typeStatus box="[430,537,1688,1712]" pageId="4" pageNumber="26">holotype</typeStatus>
:
</emphasis>
Total length: 2.00. Carapace dark brown, 1.00 long, 0.72 wide, 0.44 high, cephalic region black covered with sparse white scales (
<figureCitation box="[780,852,1724,1748]" captionStart="FIGURES 6–9" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1839,1862]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,331,1815]" captionTargetId="figure-149@3.[151,1436,331,1815]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 6–9. Soesilarishius minimus sp. nov. 6 male habitus (paratype IBSP 160758); 7 female habitus (paratype IBSP 160711). Soesilarishius crispiventer sp. nov. 8 male habitus (paratype IBSP 160801); 9 female habitus (paratype IBSP 160841)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5280704" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5280704/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="26">Figs 8</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[866,940,1724,1748]" captionStart="FIGURES 45–59" captionStartId="14.[151,264,1736,1759]" captionTargetBox="[286,1297,202,1703]" captionTargetId="figure-153@14.[271,1300,195,1716]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURES 45–59. Soesilarishius minimus sp. nov. 45–46 male carapace (45 dorsal, 46 lateral); Soesilarishius crispiventer sp. nov. 47–48 male carapace (47 dorsal, 48 lateral); Soesilarishius cymbialis sp. nov. 49–50 male carapace (49 dorsal, 50 lateral); Soesilarishius lunatus sp. nov. 51–52 male carapace (51 dorsal, 52 lateral); Soesilarishius spinipes sp. nov. 53–54 male carapace (53 dorsal, 54 lateral); Soesilarishius albipes sp. nov. 55–56 male carapace (55 dorsal, 56 lateral); Soesilarishius dromedarius sp. nov. 57–58 male carapace (57 dorsal, 58 lateral); Soesilarishius crispiventer sp. nov. 59 male abdomen, ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5280720" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5280720/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="26">47–48</figureCitation>
). Ocular quadrangle 0.53 long. Anterior eye row 0.72 wide and posterior 0.68 wide. Chelicera brown. Labium and sternum brown. Endite brown, not projected laterally. Palp light brown, with a short, stout RTA, round tegulum with poorly developed sperm loop and long, distal, curled embolus (
<figureCitation box="[383,515,1832,1856]" captionStart="FIGURES 10–14" captionStartId="5.[151,258,1573,1594]" captionTargetBox="[171,1419,205,1524]" captionTargetId="figure-215@5.[151,1436,195,1549]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 10–14. Soesilarishius crispiventer sp. nov. 10–12 left male palp (10 ventral, 11 retroventral, 12 retrolateral); 13 epigyne, ventral view; 14 vulva, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5280706" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5280706/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="26">Figs 10–12</figureCitation>
). Legs 4=312, dark brown, fading towards tarsi. Length of femur: I 0.49, II 0.45, III 0.63, IV 0.57; patella + tibia: I 0.54, II 0.50, III 0.60, IV 0.56; metatarsus + tarsus: I 0.44, II 0.40, III 0.58, IV 0.68. Spination: femur I–IV d1-1-1; patella I–II 0, III r1, IV 0; tibia I v1r-2-2 (for proportion, see 
